# Monorepo Tech and Pattern Rules

Use this as the default project context before implementing features or refactors.

## Stack Overview

- Monorepo with `backend/` (NestJS + MongoDB/Mongoose) and `frontend/` (Angular + Tailwind).
- Frontend has two Angular apps: `frontend/projects/admin-ui` and `frontend/projects/user-ui`.
- `admin-ui` uses Angular Material components.
- `user-ui` is a separate Angular application with its own routes/assets/build targets.
- Shared frontend code belongs in `frontend/projects/common-ui` (base classes, HTTP services, pipes, common utilities).

## Backend Structure

- `backend/src` is the main NestJS application.
- `backend/libs/contracts` is a shared library for frontend and backend contracts.
- Put cross-layer DTOs, commands, queries, enums, and constants in `backend/libs/contracts`.
- Keep backend internals (domain services, persistence models, private implementation details) out of contracts.

## Integration and Boundaries

- Prefer contract-first changes when backend and frontend both consume the same shape.
- If an API payload changes, update shared contracts first, then backend implementation, then frontend usage.
- Do not duplicate shared enums/constants in frontend apps when they exist in contracts.
- Keep admin-specific UI logic in `admin-ui`; move reusable logic to `common-ui`.

## Implementation Priorities

- Follow existing project conventions from starter code; extend patterns instead of introducing parallel architectures.
- Favor small, incremental edits aligned with existing module/folder structure.
- Keep public interfaces strongly typed and avoid `any` in shared boundaries.
- Document any intentional deviations from existing patterns directly in code comments near the change.
